e momentous economic and political changes following the end of the cold war fostered anxiety over migration. For Cameroonians, the question of who belongs where rises to the fore in political struggles between different tribes, while the Dutch invoke autochthony in fierce debates over the integration of immigrants. This fascinating comparative perspective allows Geschiere to examine the emotional appeal of autochthony—as well as its dubious historical basis—and to shed light on a range of important issues, such as multiculturalism, national citizenship, and migration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCosmopolitanismzCameroon. 0aCosmopolitanismzNetherlands. 0aEthnicityzCameroon. 0aEthnicityzNetherlands. 0aGroup identityzCameroon. 0aGroup identityzNetherlands. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acitizen, citizenship, africa, african, europe, european, western world, anthropology, cosmopolitan, international, global, identity, local, autochthony, rights, self, understanding, classical, history, historical, cameroon, netherlands, academic, scholarly, research, economy, economics, politics, political, dutch, immigrants, multiculturalism, migration.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022628964940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226289663423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226289663/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles